Let  
\[
S \;=\;\Bigl\{\,x=(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{6})\in\mathbb R^{6}\;\Bigm|\;
x_{i}\ge 0,\;
\sum_{i=1}^{6}x_{i}=12,\;
\sum_{i=1}^{6}x_{i}^{2}=30
\Bigr\},
\]
and  
\[
H \;=\;\Bigl\{\,y=(y_{1},\ldots ,y_{6})\in\mathbb R^{6}\;\Bigm|\;
y_{1}=y_{2}=y_{3}=s>0,\;
y_{4}=y_{5}=y_{6}=t>0,\;
s>t,\;
st=9
\Bigr\}.
\]

For \(x\in S\) and \(y\in H\) write the squared Euclidean distance  
\[
D(x,y)\;=\;\lVert x-y\rVert ^{2}
          \;=\;\sum_{i=1}^{6}(x_{i}-y_{i})^{2}.
\]

(A)  Prove that the minimum  
\[
D_{\min }=\min \bigl\{D(x,y)\;:\;x\in S,\;y\in H\bigr\}
\]
exists.

(B)  Determine the exact value of \(D_{\min}\) (expressed with rational numbers and real radicals only) and describe \emph{all} pairs \((x,y)\) that attain this minimum.



